2500|$|On 9 July 2008, <b>the</b> <b>Defense</b> <b>Secretary</b> Robert Gates put {{the tanker}} {{contract}} in an [...] "expedited recompetition" [...] with Defense Undersecretary John Young {{in charge of}} the selection process instead of the Air Force. [...] A draft of the revised RFP was provided to the contractors on 6 August 2008 for comments with the revised RFP to be finalized by mid-August. [...] Proposals would be due in October 2008 and selection was to be done by the end of 2008. [...] In mid-August, there was speculation that Boeing was considering a [...] "no bid" [...] position. [...] On 21 August 2008 Boeing asked the DoD for an additional four months to submit a proposal centered on a larger aircraft, but they opposed further delay. [...] Then on 10 September 2008, Defense Secretary Robert Gates decided that the new competition could not be fairly completed before the end of 2008. The DoD canceled the request for proposals and delayed the decision on when to issue another request until the new presidential administration was in office.|$|E
